>[Question]
>is there a formula for the sequence, 1,11,111,1111,11111,...and so 
>on?
>
>[Difficulty]
>if you look at the difference of two adjacent terms, you get powers 
>or factors of 10. but then, it seems that there is no definite 
>formula for finding the nth term of the sequence.
>
>[Thoughts]
>|1-11|=10    => 10^1
>|11-111|=100 => 10^2
>|111-1111|=1000=>10^3
>
>it is easy to use summation formula on this, summation(10^n) but 
>using a formula for finding the nth term is the one im looking for. 
>please help me on this one. thanks a lot.
>
>
>
>
>

Hi Jake,

Thanks for writing to Dr Math.  Notice that

  10^n - 1 = 9999...9999

So I think the formula you want is

  (10^n - 1)/9.

If you have any questions about this or need more help, please write
back and show me what you have been able to do, and I will try to
offer further suggestions.

- Doctor Vogler, The Math Forum
  <http://mathforum.org/dr.math/>

